name: OWASP dependency-check
description: OWASP dependency-check is a software composition analysis utility that detects publicly disclosed vulnerabilities in application dependencies.
description_good_justification: The gh-pages documentation site contains a succinct description of the project: https://jeremylong.github.io/DependencyCheck/
interact_justification: The project is on github (https://github.com/jeremylong/DependencyCheck), the project does provide an issue template (https://github.com/jeremylong/DependencyCheck/tree/master/.github) so that users know what to provide, the documentation site (https://jeremylong.github.io/DependencyCheck/) contains information about getting help.
contribution_justification: Projects on GitHub by default use issues and pull requests, as encouraged by documentation such as <https://guides.github.com/activities/contributing-to-open-source/>.
contribution_requirements_justification: All Pull Requests are built using travis-ci and reviewed using Codacy. As one can see in this PR (https://github.com/jeremylong/DependencyCheck/pull/673) - contributes are fixing code quality issues. As codacy runs on every PR submitters are notified of any issues. The Codacy dashboard can be found here: https://www.codacy.com/app/OWASP_Reviews/DependencyCheck/dashboard
license_location_justification: Non-trivial license location file in repository: <https://github.com/jeremylong/DependencyCheck/blob/master/LICENSE.txt>.
floss_license_justification: The Apache-2.0 license is approved by the Open Source Initiative (OSI).
floss_license_osi_justification: The Apache-2.0 license is approved by the Open Source Initiative (OSI).
documentation_basics_justification: The https://github.com/jeremylong/DependencyCheck/blob/master/README.md file on the home page of the repo explains how to obtain and use dependency-check. The readme provides links to the gh-pages documentation site (https://jeremylong.github.io/DependencyCheck/) which has additional usage information.
documentation_interface_justification: The gh-pages site (http://jeremylong.github.io/DependencyCheck/) documents how to configure and use dependency-check. Additionnally, the documentation site contains a "how to read the reports" page (http://jeremylong.github.io/DependencyCheck/general/thereport.html). "The how to read the reports" page is also linked from the report generated by dependency-check (see a sample here: http://jeremylong.github.io/DependencyCheck/general/SampleReport.html.
repo_public_justification: Repository on GitHub, which provides public git repositories with URLs.
repo_track_justification: Repository on GitHub, which uses git. git can track the changes, who made them, and when they were made.
repo_interim_justification: Changes are incrementally added to the github repo for review. Multiple PRs are available for review (both from the core team and from other contributors).
repo_distributed_justification: Repository on GitHub, which uses git. git is distributed.
version_unique_justification: The application uses Maven versioning, each release is tagged in the github repo.
version_tags_justification: each release is tagged in github.
release_notes_justification: Release notes are contained in the google groups postings: https://groups.google.com/forum/#!forum/dependency-check
release_notes_vulns_justification: The only security related issues was addressed via a PR (https://github.com/jeremylong/DependencyCheck/pull/589). This was included in the release notes.
report_process_justification: The project uses GitHub issues (https://github.com/jeremylong/DependencyCheck/issues). Additionally, the HTML report includes links to the github issues page (sample report: https://jeremylong.github.io/DependencyCheck/general/SampleReport.html). The project also has a google groups mailing list: https://groups.google.com/forum/#!forum/dependency-check
report_responses_justification: The core team has been very good about responding to tickets: https://github.com/jeremylong/DependencyCheck/issues. In most cases an initial response occurs within a week.
enhancement_responses_justification: Again, looking at the track record of the project (https://github.com/jeremylong/DependencyCheck/issues), I believe we have met this requirement.
report_archive_justification: As the project uses github issues, this is baked in: https://github.com/jeremylong/DependencyCheck/issues
vulnerability_report_response_justificat: The only security related issue identified was fixed via a PR and merged within 2 days: https://github.com/jeremylong/DependencyCheck/pull/589
build_floss_tools_justification: The application can be built using Maven and openJDK.
test_justification: The project contains standard unit and integration tests.
test_invocation_justification: test suite can be run using `mvn verify`
test_most_justification:
Current test coverage can be found here: 
https://jeremylong.github.io/DependencyCheck/dependency-check-core/cobertura/index.html
https://jeremylong.github.io/DependencyCheck/dependency-check-utils/cobertura/index.html
https://jeremylong.github.io/DependencyCheck/dependency-check-ant/cobertura/index.html
https://jeremylong.github.io/DependencyCheck/dependency-check-maven/cobertura/index.html
https://jeremylong.github.io/DependencyCheck/dependency-check-cli/cobertura/index.html
test_policy_justification: Please see the pull request template: https://github.com/jeremylong/DependencyCheck/blob/master/.github/pull_request_template.md and the contributing guideline: https://github.com/jeremylong/DependencyCheck/blob/master/.github/contributing.md
tests_are_added_justification:
Codacy test coverage can be found here: https://www.codacy.com/app/OWASP_Reviews/DependencyCheck/dashboard

Going forward, test cases have been being added for major changes. There is some older functionality that has not been updated that should have some test cases written.
tests_documented_added_justification: Please see the pull request template: https://github.com/jeremylong/DependencyCheck/blob/master/.github/pull_request_template.md and the contributing guideline: https://github.com/jeremylong/DependencyCheck/blob/master/.github/contributing.md
warnings_justification: The project uses codacy (https://www.codacy.com/app/OWASP_Reviews/DependencyCheck/dashboard), checkstyle (http://jeremylong.github.io/DependencyCheck/dependency-check-core/checkstyle.html), etc.
warnings_fixed_justification: Most warnings have been resolved. A handful of code complexity issues remain that will be addressed in the future.
warnings_strict_justification: This suggestion has not been met.
know_secure_design_justification: Jeremy Long, the founder and core contributor to OWASP dependency-check. Please see his linkedin profile for information security related work: https://www.linkedin.com/in/jeremy-long-52258a2/
know_common_errors_justification: Jeremy Long, the founder and core contributor to OWASP dependency-check. Please see his linkedin profile for information security related work: https://www.linkedin.com/in/jeremy-long-52258a2/
crypto_published_justification: No cryptographic functions are used to protect information. SHA1 and MD5 are used for file identification.
crypto_call_justification: Message digest algorithms are used from the JCE
crypto_floss_justification: Message Digests are calculated using JCE.
crypto_keylength_justification: No cryptographic keys are used. The project only uses hashing.
crypto_working_justification: While the project does generated MD5 hashes of the files scanned - this is not used for any cryptographic purpose. The SHA1 is also calculated; but even this is not used for any cryptographic security function.
delivery_mitm_justification: The application utilizes HTTPS URLs for retrieving data from NIST.
delivery_unsigned_justification: SHA1SUM is not used over HTTP.
static_analysis_fixed_justification: All findings from scan (https://scan.coverity.com/projects/dependencycheck) have been fixed.
static_analysis_often_justification: Tools such as PMD, checkstyle, and findbugs are run on every commit via the travis-ci builds. Coverity's scan (The project uses Coverity's scan: https://scan.coverity.com/projects/dependencycheck) is run at least once prior to release.
dynamic_analysis_justification: This suggested practice is not practical for a build tool such as dependency-check. There is no UI to test.
dynamic_analysis_unsafe_justification: The project is written in Java.
dynamic_analysis_enable_assertions_justi: Dynamic analysis does not occur as this is not a web application.
dynamic_analysis_fixed_justification: dynamic analysis is not performed on the application as it is a build tool not a web application.
crypto_weaknesses_justification: The project does use SHA1 hashing because FOSS repose such as Maven Central utilize SHA1. The SHA1 algorithm is not used a security critical manor.
discussion_justification: GitHub supports discussions on issues and pull requests. In addition to GitHub, the project also uses a google group: https://groups.google.com/forum/#!forum/dependency-check
english_justification: The GitHub site, documentation pages, etc. are all in English.
hardening_justification: As this is a build plugin, there are fewer hardening mechanisms that need to be in place. However, one of the major ones is XML validation with prevention against XXE/XEE.
crypto_used_network_justification: All URLs used in the default configuration are HTTPS.
crypto_certificate_verification_justific: URLs to retrieve data from the Internet are HTTPS,
crypto_verification_private_justificatio: No private information is sent. While some URLs are used - by default HTTPS is used.
hardened_site_justification:
